<h2 id="frequently-asked-questions">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<p><strong>Q: Can I have multiple personal loans at the same time?</strong></p>
<p>A: Yes, you can have multiple personal loans, but lenders will consider your total debt service ratio. Most lenders prefer total monthly debt payments (including the new loan) to be under 60-70% of your monthly income. Each additional loan application will be evaluated based on your remaining borrowing capacity.</p>
<p>Banks typically allow 2-3 active personal loans maximum. Non-bank lenders may be more flexible but will assess your total affordability carefully. Having multiple loans may also affect your credit score and future borrowing ability.</p>
<p><strong>Q: What happens if I cannot pay my personal loan?</strong></p>
<p>A: If you cannot pay your personal loan:</p>
<p><strong>Early Action Steps:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Contact your lender immediately to explain situation</li>
<li>Request payment deferment or restructuring</li>
<li>Negotiate reduced payment plan temporarily</li>
<li>Seek financial counseling assistance</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Consequences of Default:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Late payment penalties and interest charges</li>
<li>Negative impact on credit score and CCRIS record</li>
<li>Legal action and possible court judgment</li>
<li>Garnishment of salary or bank accounts (with court order)</li>
<li>Difficulty obtaining future credit</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Prevention Strategies:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Build emergency fund covering 3-6 months payments</li>
<li>Consider loan protection insurance</li>
<li>Monitor your finances regularly</li>
<li>Communicate early with lender if facing difficulties</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Q: Is it better to get a larger loan amount with lower monthly payments or smaller amount with higher payments?</strong></p>
<p>A: This depends on your financial situation and risk tolerance:</p>
<p><strong>Larger Loan, Lower Payments Benefits:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Better cash flow management</li>
<li>More flexibility in monthly budget</li>
<li>Lower stress from payment obligations</li>
<li>Ability to invest surplus funds</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Larger Loan, Lower Payments Drawbacks:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Higher total interest paid over time</li>
<li>Longer debt obligation period</li>
<li>More exposure to interest rate changes</li>
<li>Less equity built quickly</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Smaller Loan, Higher Payments Benefits:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Less total interest paid</li>
<li>Faster debt clearance</li>
<li>Lower overall financial risk</li>
<li>Better debt-to-income ratio sooner</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Choose the option that allows you to comfortably make payments even during lean months while minimizing total interest cost.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Can foreigners get personal loans in Malaysia?</strong></p>
<p>A: Yes, but options are very limited:</p>
<p><strong>Eligible Foreigners:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Expatriates with valid work permits</li>
<li>Malaysia My Second Home (MM2H) participants</li>
<li>Permanent residents</li>
<li>Long-term employment pass holders</li>
